<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0; text-indent: 0.5in">&#160;</p>

<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0">Kiora Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) hereby furnishes
the updated investor presentation attached as Exhibit 99.1 to this Current Report on Form 8-K, which the Company may use in presentations
to investors from time to time<span style="color: #2E518C">.</span></p>

<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0">&#160;</p>

<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0">The information furnished pursuant to Item 7.01, including Exhibit
99.1, shall not be deemed &#8220;filed&#8221; for the purposes of Section 18 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#8220;Exchange
Act&#8221;) and will not be deemed to be incorporated by reference into any filing under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, or the
Exchange Act, except to the extent that the Company specifically incorporates it by reference.</p>

<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0">&#160;</p>

<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0pt 0">The information furnished in this report, including Exhibit 99.1, shall
not be deemed to constitute an admission that such information or exhibit is required to be furnished pursuant to Regulation FD or that
such information or exhibit contains material information that is not otherwise publicly available. In addition, the Company does not
assume any obligation to update such information or exhibit in the future.</p>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White"> 2 Forward Looking Statements Some of the statements in this press release are &#8220;forward - looking&#8221; and are made pursuant to the safe harbor provision of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 . These &#8220;forward - looking&#8221; statements include statements relating to, among other things, the development and commercialization efforts and other regulatory or marketing approval efforts pertaining to Kiora&#8217;s products, including KIO - 101 , KIO - 201 and KIO - 301 , as well as the success thereof, with such approvals or success may not be obtained or achieved on a timely basis or at all . These statements involve risks and uncertainties that may cause results to differ materially from the statements set forth in this press release, including, among other things, market and other conditions and certain risk factors described under the heading &#8220;Risk Factors&#8221; contained in Kiora&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10 - K filed with the SEC on March 25 , 2021 or described in Kiora&#8217;s other public filings . Kiora&#8217;s results may also be affected by factors of which Kiora is not currently aware . The forward - looking statements in this press release speak only as of the date of this press release . Kiora expressly disclaims any obligation or undertaking to release publicly any updates or revisions to such statements to reflect any change in its expectations with regard thereto or any changes in the events, conditions, or circumstances on which any such statement is based, except as required by law .</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">3 Addressing Unmet Needs in Eye Care New Leadership  &#8211; Renewed Focus &#9642; Efficient investment to clinical inflection  points Compelling Value Proposition Diversified Portfolio Revolutionary small molecule with the potential to restore vision in patients  with inherited or age - related retinal degeneration &#9642; Unique small molecule MOA restores light perception  &#9642; Entering Ph1b in Q3 2022 Eye drop to accelerate ocular wound healing and protect the ocular surface &#9642; Next generation cross - linked hyaluronic acid (HA) &#9642; Ph3b ready Small molecule DHODH inhibitor to treat immunologic eye disease &#9642; Validated disease modifying target in rheumatology &#9642; Ph1b trial reported safety, tolerability and significant reduction in clinical sign Large &amp; Underserved Market Opportunities &#9642; Transformative and reprioritized pipeline</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White"> 5 KIO - 301 Small Molecule  Photoswitch for Retinal Reanimation</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 5 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img06.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">6 Prevalence &#9642; 1:3,000 - 1:5,000 (Orphan Disease) Etiology &#9642; 50+ genetically distinct subtypes from 150+ mutations &#9642; Inherited disease Clinical Presentation &#9642; Night blindness, reduced visual field range and eventual loss of central vision &#9642; Visual acuity declines Diagnosis &#9642; Retinal exam (black bone - spicule pigmentation ) &#9642; ERG provides definitive diagnosis &#9642; Genetic testing Retinitis Pigmentosa (RP)  Disease Overview KIO - 301 is mutation agnostic American Academy of Ophthalmology</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 6 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img07.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">7 RP  &#8211; How Retinal Degeneration Occurs &#9642; Normal human retina has about 120 million rods (black &amp; white, night vision, movement) and 6 million cones (color) &#9642; Photoreceptors die (rods first, then cones), unable to activate Bipolar cells and Retinal Ganglion Cells (RGCs) &#9642; Bipolar cells and RGCs remain intact and retain ability to send signals to the brain Photoreceptors (rods and cones) sense light  and pass the signal to special transmitting cells Bipolar cells and RGCs relay signal from rods and  cones to the brain, where the image is &#8220;processed&#8221; RGC Cone Rod Bipolar Cell To the brain (connection intact)</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 7 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img08.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White"> 8 KIO - 301 Turns RGCs &#8220;ON&#8221; in the Presence of Light Neuron. 92, 100 - 113 (2016) trans cis 1. In RP, photoreceptors are no longer viable and therefore their companion &#8220;signal&#8221; cells (RGCs) are not capable of being activ ate d  or set to &#8220;OFF&#8221; 2. KIO - 301 preferentially enters these &#8220;OFF&#8221; RGCs and turns them &#8220;ON&#8221; in the presence of light*  * Visual light causes shape change  of KIO - 301  (trans  &#10230; cis), blocking the movement of positively charged ions out of the cell through  the  K v /HCN channels. This build up of charged ions in the cell triggers activation (phototransduction signaling) to the brain.   Intracellular KIO - 301 P2X7 Extracellular K V /HCN Channels KIO - 301 lodges inside ion  channels. In presence of light,  blocks ion outflow,  causing cell  activation.</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 8 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">9 Moonlight 100w Incandescent Light Bulb Cloudy Day Sunlight Light Intensity (photons/cm 2 &#183; sec) KIO - 301: Light Intensity and Wavelength Sci. Rep. 7, 45487 (2017), Banghart,  Trauner et al (2008) Wavelength (nm) Light Response Index</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 9 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">10 Investigator led safety assessment along and between cohorts  KIO - 301 X &#181;g KIO - 301 Y &#181;g KIO - 301 Y &#181;g KIO - 301 Z &#181;g 3 Patients (NLP/LP) Contralateral eye of same pts Single IVT dosing (Y &gt; X) Same schedule of activities 3 Patients (HM) 3 Patients (NLP/LP) Cohort 1 X &lt; Y &lt; Z Day 1 Day 2, 4, 7, 14, 28 Worse eye Single IVT dosing (single eye) Safety,  pK (plasma), and efficacy Day 1 Day 2, 4, 7, 14, 28 Worse eye Single IVT dosing (single eye) Safety,  pK (plasma), and efficacy 3 Patients (HM) Contralateral eye of same pts Single IVT dosing (Y &gt; X) Same schedule of activities Open Label, Single Ascending Dose Trial  &#8211; Royal Adelaide Hospital, Australia KIO - 301: Phase 1b Study Design</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">11 KIO - 101 Potential 1st in Class Treatment for Ocular Manifestations  of Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 11 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img12.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">12 Ocular Involvement of RA  Overview Large unmet need &#9642; 3.3 million people in United States have RA &#9642; &gt;30% of these patients have ocular manifestations (~1.1m) &#9642; Ocular signs &amp; symptoms are the most common, non - articular manifestations of RA Patient Journey Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) is a chronic, systemic autoimmune disease  that primarily  effects joint linings, causing swelling, bone erosion and deformity &#9642; No cure exists but symptoms can be managed with disease modifying medications &#9642; DHODH inhibitors, IL - 6, TNF - &#945; antagonists and others Rheumatol Int. 2017 Sep;37(9):1551 - 1557.  Eyenet Magazine. 2016 Nov:37 - 9.  IVOS . 2015 Jun;56(7):4437. &#8220;The immune attack on the  surface of the eye is a mirror  image of what is destroying the  joint synovium&#8221; - Sandeep Jain, MD,  Univ of Illinois, College of Med  Rheumatology Ophthalmology OTC Tear Rx  DED Drops</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 12 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img13.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">13 RA Ocular Signs &amp;  Symptoms are Mediated  by T Cells KIO - 101 acts upstream to inhibit  proliferation of T helper cells (Th1 and  Th17) in lymph node and on - site to  suppress pro - inflammatory cytokine release Arch  Ophthalmol . 2012 Jan;130(1):90 - 100</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 13 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">21 Ocular Surface Diseases American Academy of Ophthalmology  ~5 million US patients Refractive surgeries (e.g., PRK) Cataracts Collagen cross - linking 9% Wounds: Surgery ~18 million US patients Episodic/mild Moderate  Severe &#402;&#404; &#1143; Epitheliopathies: Dry Eye ~2 million US patients Injuries/abrasions Chemical burns Difficult to heal PED/ulcers 3% Wounds: Trauma ~28 million US patients Contact lens wear Ocular irritants Glaucoma medications 53% Epitheliopathies:  Non - Dry Eye</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 21 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img22.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White">&#401;&#401; Refractive Surgery Overview American Academy of Ophthalmology, Ocular Surgery News: April 10, 2019 &#9642; PRK is a surgical correction of refractive  errors for patients who are not suitable  candidates for LASIK due to: &gt; Inadequate corneal thickness  &gt; Larger pupil size &gt; Dry eye &gt; Anterior basement membrane  disease &#9642; PRK involves controlled mechanical  removal of corneal epithelium with  subsequent lasering of stroma  &#9642; While PRK yields superior visual  results, complications include: &gt; Post - operative pain &gt; Risk of infection &gt; Corneal haze &gt; Decreased contrast sensitivity  &gt; Slower visual recovery  &#9642; Standard - of - care is a Bandage  Contact Lens (BCL) which can result  in subsequent erosion of epithelium &#9642; Enabling the epithelium to heal faster  may mitigate peri - operative  complications and improve long - term  visual outcomes &#9642; The PRK population is ideal: &gt; Large population (~850,000  LASIK/PRK surgeries per year in  the US) &gt; Large wound (9mm), same size for  all patients and known time zero &gt; Time to healing well - established PRK The Unmet Need 7KH&#3;2SSRUWXQLW\</P>

<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 22 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="break-before: page; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 100%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><IMG SRC="tm222495d1_ex99-1img23.jpg" ALT=""></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 1px; color: White"> 23 KIO - 201 &#9642; KIO - 201 is based on a modified form of the natural polymer hyaluronic acid (HA)  &#9642; HA is a material with a high viscosity that promotes wound healing by enabling enhanced cell migration &#9642; 5 clinical trials completed (3 PRK surgical recovery and 2 dry eye)  &gt; Approximately 400 eyes have been treated with KIO - 201  &gt; Strong safety and efficacy profile Crosslinking Creates Unique Attributes Ideal for Ocular Surface &#9642; Improved product stability &#9642; Longer retention on the ocular surface over non - crosslinked HA (2 hours vs minutes) &#9642; Able to achieve concentrations up to 7.5x current products &#9642; Decreased viscosity during blinking = no blurred vision Non - Crosslinked Crosslink</P>

// Edgar(tm) Renderer was created by staff of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.  Data and content created by government employees within the scope of their employment are not subject to domestic copyright protection. 17 U.S.C. 105.
var Show={};Show.LastAR=null,Show.showAR=function(a,r,w){if(Show.LastAR)Show.hideAR();var e=a;while(e&&e.nodeName!='TABLE')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e||e.nodeName!='TABLE'){var ref=((window)?w.document:document).getElementById(r);if(ref){e=ref.cloneNode(!0);
e.removeAttribute('id');a.parentNode.appendChild(e)}}
if(e)e.style.display='block';Show.LastAR=e};Show.hideAR=function(){Show.LastAR.style.display='none'};Show.toggleNext=function(a){var e=a;while(e.nodeName!='DIV')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e.style){}else if(!e.style.display){}else{var d,p_;if(e.style.display=='none'){d='block';p='-'}else{d='none';p='+'}
e.style.display=d;if(a.textContent){a.textContent=p+a.textContent.substring(1)}else{a.innerText=p+a.innerText.substring(1)}}}

/* Updated 2009-11-04 */
/* v2.2.0.24 */

/* DefRef Styles */
..report table.authRefData{
	background-color: #def;
	border: 2px solid #2F4497;
	font-size: 1em;
	position: absolute;
}

	display: block;
	font-weight: bold;
}

	margin-top: 0px;
}

}

	background-color: #2F4497;
}

	height: 150px;
	overflow: auto;
	width: 400px;
}

	font-size: 1em;
}

	color: black;
	text-decoration: none;
}

	background-color: white;
